\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Funding Global Public Good Institutions via taxes on aviation emissions-
 a comparison of three proposed mechanisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Lennart Stern
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
lennart.stern@ens.fr
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The EU is considering unilateral action to achieve higher carbon pricing
 for international aviation.
 It has been proposed that the EU could start a club mechanism whereby participa
ting countries would allocate a certain proportion of aviation carbon pricing
 revenue to some agreed-upon global institution for climate change mitigation.
 We propose an alternative club mechanism in which participating countries
 that give up the right to keep any of the carbon pricing revenue would
 be allowed to allocate this revenue to global public good institutions
 (GPGIs) of their choice.
 We consider an example where the set of GPGIs recognised as eligible includes
 2 GPGIs for global health as well as 4 for climate change mitigation.
 In the numerical simulations this alternative mechanism can achieve 13%
 more expected gains for global welfare than the one currently proposed.
 At the Nash equilibria most participating countries give up the right to
 retain any money so that they can affect the allocation of money in favor
 of the GPGIs that they prefer.
 We then enrich this mechanism by adding the possibility for countries to
 support a set of GPGIs by giving money to so-called Proportional Matching
 Funds, which then distribute it to the GPGIs in proportion to the allocations
 made to them by others.
 In the numerical simulations we find that this further enhances participation
 incentives and allows 29% more expected global welfare to be generated
 than the currently proposed mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\emph on
Introduction
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Introduction"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through the Carbon Offsetting and Reduction Scheme for International Aviation
 (CORSIA) the participating countries will oblige airlines to offset a part
 of their emissions by buying certificates for projects that have been certified
 to have reduced emission.
 CORSIA thus has the potential to improve global welfare in two ways: firstly,
 causing reductions in aviation emissions due to the carbon price that airlines
 will face.
 Secondly, through the money generated for the offset projects that will
 be financed through the sale of emissions reductions certificates to airlines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The offset eligibility standard under CORSIA is currently under negotiation.
 Depending on the standard chosen, different types of projects will get
 financed, such as REDD projects for reducing tropical deforestation or
 Clean Development Mechanism (CDM) projects for financing renewable energy
 projects in developing countries.
 A further dimension in which offset standards differ is their stringency.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Warnecke et al. (2019)"
target "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41558-019-0415-y"

\end_inset

 find that under some offset eligibility rules that have been proposed,
 demand from CORSIA would be met by projects that would continue anyway
 and the price for the offsets per ton of 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 would drop below $1.
 Based on this concern, France, the Netherlands, Portugal, Belgium, Austria,
 Finland and Norway have threatened independently to withdraw from the agreement
 if the offset eligibility standards are not chosen stringent enough.
 The EU is considering instituting further carbon pricing policies for internati
onal aviation in parallel to CORSIA.
 This study will compare 3 proposals for club mechanisms for taxing emissions
 from international aviation and raising money for Global Public Good Institutio
ns (GPGIs) that groups of countries such as the EU could initiate.
 By a GPGI we shall mean any institution that uses money to cause increases
 in the provision of a particular global public good.
 One example of a GPGI is a carbon offset standard like the one that will
 be chosen for CORSIA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first proposal that we will define, named CORSIA+, is based on suggestions
 that were commonly made in response to a public consultation held by the
 EU on the question of which carbon pricing policies to pursue for international
 aviation.
 In CORSIA+, participating countries would be obliged to tax at an agreed-upon
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 all emissions from outgoing international flights as well as all emissions
 from flights coming in from non-participating countries.
 Each participating country would be allowed to retain for itself a proportion
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 (called the retention rate parameter) of the tax revenue collected.
 The remaining part of the tax revenue would be allocated to an agreed-upon
 GPGI for climate change mitigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We study the likely outcomes for different values of the retention rate
 parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 in a model that we also use to analyze the other mechanism that we propose.
 In the model the world is partitioned into the 12 regional blocks of countries
 of the RICE model 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "(Nordhaus 2010)"
target "https://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies/28461#"

\end_inset

, each of which is assumed to act as a unitary player maximizing the aggregate
 payoffs of the countries that it comprises.
 We focus on the case of a small tax rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that CORSIA+ would oblige participants to impose on emissions from internationa
l flights and estimate the countries' payoffs for this case.
 The assumption of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 being small is made  to simplify the model, allowing us to make several
 linearity assumptions.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As we will argue in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Overall-comparison-of"

\end_inset

, the results about the comparative performance of the different mechanisms
 will plausibly hold for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To estimate the payoffs in the game we use data and econometric estimates
 where possible, whilst resorting to several ad hoc assumptions where this
 appears necessary.
 We use an iterated best response algorithm that starts with a set of players
 that roughly correspond to the current participants in the CORSIA treaty.
 At each step of the algorithm a randomly selected player is given the opportuni
ty to adjust his strategy to play a best response to the other players'
 strategy profile at that step.
 For the mechanisms studied, the algorithm always terminates, meaning that
 we always reach a Nash equilibrium.
 For CORSIA+ we find that for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\leq0.35$
\end_inset

 we always reach a Nash equilibrium with no participation and for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0.5$
\end_inset

 we always reach a Nash equilibrium with full participation, whilst for
 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0.4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0.45$
\end_inset

 either of theses outcomes can occur, depending on the random realisations
 of the draws made in the iterated best response algorithm.
 The question arises as to whether we could modify CORSIA+ so as to enhance
 participation incentives in other ways than by increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The alternative mechanisms that we will propose in this article are motivated
 by this question and answer it in the affirmative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first alternative proposal is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Simple MGF Mechanism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which stands for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\series bold
M
\series default
ultiple 
\series bold
G
\series default
lobal Public Good Institution 
\series bold
F
\series default
inancing 
\series bold
Mechanism
\series default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In this mechanism participants would not be obliged to allocate money to
 a single fixed GPGI, as is the case in CORSIA and CORSIA+.
 Instead, there would be a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of GPGIs that would be recognized as being eligible for receiving money
 through the mechanisms.
 Participants would be given two options.
 The first is to participate 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

with the right to allocate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In this case the participant would have to allocate all the tax revenue
 collected to the GPGIs from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The second option is to participate 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

without the right to allocate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in which case the country could retain a proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 of the tax revenue collected.
 The money not retained by those participating without right to allocate
 is given to the GPGIs in proportion to the allocations made to them by
 those who participate with right to allocate.
 Thereby the effective influence of those participating with right to allocate
 is enhanced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the numerical simulations we find that the Simple MGF mechanism can achieve
 13% more gains in expected welfare than CORSIA+.
 At the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 that maximises the expected welfare for the Simple MGF mechanism, 37% more
 money is raised for GPGIs than under CORSIA+ wtih the correponding value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 At the Nash equilibria reached under the Simple MGF Mechanism many players
 choose to participate with right to allocate, thus allocating all the tax
 revenue that they collect to GPGIs and retaining none of it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To further enhance the incentives to participate with the right to allocate,
 we enrich the mechanism by allowing countries to give to so-called All-Encompas
sing Proportional Matching Funds (AEPMFs).
 For each subset 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 of size at least 2 of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of eligible GPGIs, there would be a corresponding AEPMF.
 An AEPMF for a set 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 of GPGIs would each month distribute the money it has received during the
 month to the GPGIs in 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

, in proportion to the amounts that these GPGIs have received from all other
 sources (i.e.
 as direct allocations or from other AEPMFs) during that month.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the numerical simulations the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs performs best.
 At the value of retention rate parameter that maximises the expected welfare
 generated by the MGF with AEPMFs, 29% more welfare is generated and 47%
 more tax revenue is raised than under CORSIA+ for the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 that maximises expected welfare for the latter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The article is organised as follows.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Related-Literature"

\end_inset

 we review some of the literature on the broader question that this study
 contributes to: How to design mechanisms to increase the provision of global
 public goods? Then we provide some background information on CORSIA in
 section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Mechanisms-to-price"

\end_inset

.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-CORSIA+-proposal"

\end_inset

 we report some suggestions for unilateral policies to price emissions from
 international aviation that were made in response to a public consultation
 held by the EU.
 Based on these suggestions, we define CORSIA+.
 Then, in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:A-model-1"

\end_inset

, we describe the model with which we analyze the different proposed mechanisms.
 In section section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "3 sec: The-Multiple-Cause"

\end_inset

 we define the MGF mechanisms.
 We briefly describe 6 GPGIs that contribute in different ways to climate
 change mitigation and global health.
 The numerical simulations are done, assuming that the set of eligible GPGIs
 for the MGF mechanisms consists of these 6 GPGIs.
 We provide a preview of the payoffs with an explanation in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "3 sec: The-Multiple-Cause"

\end_inset

.
 The detailed description of the methods used to compute these payoffs is
 provided in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Explanation"

\end_inset

.
 This section can be skipped if one believes that the payoff estimates are
 plausible.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Estimates-of-Payoffs"

\end_inset

shows the results for the payoffs.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Numerical-simulations"

\end_inset

 reports some results for the numerical simulations, whilst more detailed
 results are provided in appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "part:A-more-detailed"

\end_inset

.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "8 sec:Conclusion"

\end_inset

 concludes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Related-Literature"

\end_inset

Related literature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Nordhaus (2015)"
target "http://econ.sciences-po.fr/sites/default/files/file/Climate%20Clubs%3A%20Overcoming%20Free-riding%20in%20International%20Climate%20Policy%20-%20aer.15000001.pdf"

\end_inset

 proposes a club mechanism to increase carbon pricing around the world.
 Members in the club would be obliged to establish a carbon price of at
 least some agreed-upon level and to apply punitive ad-valorem tariffs on
 all goods that are imported from non-participating countries.
 Nordhaus emphasizes the risk that such a mechanism could pose to the world
 trading system.
 Non-participates might retaliate, which could possibly lead to a trade
 war.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It would therefore be valuable if mechanisms could be designed that would
 increase the incentives for global public good provision without resorting
 to punitive sanctions on non-participants.
 One potential source for such incentives that has been studied in the literatur
e (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Barrett (2005)"
target "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1574009905030287"

\end_inset

 for a survey) is the following: treaties can restructure the strategic
 interaction between countries, transforming it into a three stage game
 where in the first stage countries decide whether to participate, in the
 second stage participants act jointly and in the third stage non-participants
 play a best response.
 The more countries participate, the greater the contributions decided in
 the second stage.
 As a result, participation incentives emerge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Incorporating this logic into a model of the Paris agreement's pledge and
 review bargaining, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Harstad (2018)"
target "https://ideas.repec.org/p/ces/ceswps/_7296.html"

\end_inset

 finds that the level of emissions abatement attainable through this is
 rather limited.
 One way to enhance incentives that he proposes is to use conditional matching
 offers, where countries would commit to abating more if the others abate
 more.
 If these matching offers are credible, then the incentives for each country
 to abate are enhanced because by doing so it will be able to cause others
 to abate more.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Harstad (2016)"
target "https://www.belfercenter.org/sites/default/files/legacy/files/2016-10_paris-agreement-beyond_v4.pdf#page=39"

\end_inset

 notes that negotiating conditional offers are time-consuming and costly.
 Furthermore, he finds that a series of short-term commitment periods lead
 to a hold-up problem with under-investments in green technology.
 Based on this, he proposes that conditional pledges should be expressed
 according to pre-specified formulas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conditional matching for contributions on a single dimension (e.g.
 national emissions reduction) with pre-specified formulas has been studied,
 amongst others, by Guttman’s (1978, 1987),
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Guttman (1987)"
target "https://www.jstor.org/stable/2554340"

\end_inset

, Rübbelke (2006) and Boadway et al.
 (2011) in a two stage game: Emissions abatement is divided into an unconditiona
l and a conditional abatement.
 Countries simultaneously declare matching factors, which define how much
 conditional abatement they will contribute for a unit of unconditional
 abatement contributed by each of the other countries.
 Assuming countries can commit to the matching factors they declare, this
 scheme allows countries to alter the incentives of other countries.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Molina et al. (2019)"
target "https://osf.io/preprints/socarxiv/7yc3g/"

\end_inset

 rigorously prove the remarkable result that in the case of two countries
 there is a unique subgame perfect Nash equilibrium in this game and at
 this equilibrium efficient levels of abatement are reached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One practical difficulty for the implementation of such conditional matching
 mechanisms is that abatement measures might be difficult to compare.
 Moreover, it might not be credible that countries will follow through on
 their commitments.
 This might necessitate using the threat of sanctions to make the commitments
 credible (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Harstad (2016)"
target "https://www.belfercenter.org/sites/default/files/legacy/files/2016-10_paris-agreement-beyond_v4.pdf#page=39"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The use of sanctions for this seems a lot less problematic than applying
 punitive sanction to non-participants to an agreement.
 If sanctions are used to help countries to voluntarily commit to following
 through on matching offers, these sanctions might never actually be applied
 and yet be effective.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In contrast to this, in the MGF mechanisms that we will propose incentives
 to contribute money to GPGIs are created without any reliance on countries'
 ability to commit.
 On the other hand, the mechanisms that we propose are far less ambitious
 than the conditional matching mechanisms analyzed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Molina et al. (2019)"
target "https://osf.io/preprints/socarxiv/7yc3g/"

\end_inset

.
 The amount of cooperation achieved is fundamentally limited by how much
 money is raised for GPGIs via the aviation emissions taxes.
 The mechanisms we propose could serve as a potential incremental opportunity
 to raise money for GPGIs and thereby complement other mechanisms for global
 public good provision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current article also contributes to the literature on collective decision
 making about multidimensional policy vectors.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Benjamin et al (2013)"
target "https://www.nber.org/papers/w18787.pdf"

\end_inset

 propose a mechanism, called Normalized Gradient Addition, in which each
 agent is asked to report a preferred direction for policy change by selecting
 a point on the unit sphere in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the dimension of the policy space.
 The policy change implemented is a weighted sum of the reported preferred
 directions for change.
 This mechanism is first order strategy proof.
 It is closely related to quadratic voting, for which efficiency results
 have been proved (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Benjamin et al (2017)"
target "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5649642/"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Posner and Weyl (2017)"
target "https://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://scholar.google.de/&httpsredir=1&article=1102&context=law_econ"

\end_inset

).
 In future work we intend to study the mechanism obtained by combining the
 MGF mechanism with the Normalised Gradient Addition mechanism instead of
 with All-Encompassing Proportional Matching Funds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper we only study a case where the overall money raised is small,
 so that the countries' payoffs are linear in the money reaching the different
 GPGIs.
 It will be interesting to see in future work how the MGF mechanism with
 All-Encompassing Proportional Matching Funds (AEPMFs) (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Definition-of-Proposal 4"

\end_inset

) will perform in a model where there are decreasing marginal returns to
 money going to the different GPGIs.
 An alternative mechanism with which the MGF mechanism could be combined
 (instead of with the AEPMFs) is the Liberal Radicalism Mechanism that was
 proposed for philanthropic Matching Funds by 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Beterin, Hitzig, Weyl (2018)"
target "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3243656"

\end_inset

.
 Remarkably, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Beterin, Hitzig, Weyl (2018)"
target "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3243656"

\end_inset

 prove that the Liberal Radicalism Mechanism can implement the first best
 as a Nash equilibrium
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is assuming, as is common in the literature (such as on the VCG mechanism),
 that each agent can neglect the cost of public funds.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In their analysis it is assumed that the government can raise any tax revenue
 required for the donation matching.
 This assumption, whilst valid for the context of public goods within a
 country, no longer holds for global public goods, given the absence of
 a world government.
 The starting point of the current paper is that global public goods are
 all underprovided and that the mechanisms studied will not achieve anything
 near an efficient level of global public good provision.
 From this it follows that there are two opportunities to increase global
 welfare: rasing more money for GPGIs and improving the allocative efficiency
 of the distribution across the different GPGIs of whatever money is raised.
 The results on the Liberal Radicalism Mechanism proved in 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Beterin, Hitzig, Weyl (2018)"
target "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3243656"

\end_inset

 suggest that grafting this mechanism onto the MGF mechanism will plausibly
 lead to higher allocative efficiency than the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs.
 However, the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs might raise more money for GPGIs.
 Future research could study the relative overall performance of these mechanism
s.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Mechanisms-to-price"

\end_inset

Mechanisms to price carbon emissions from international aviation that have
 been or are being attempted 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-EU's-unilateral"

\end_inset

The EU's unilateral inclusion of international aviation in the EU Emissions
 Trading Scheme (ETS) (measure taken in 2012 and suspended in 2013)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2012 the EU extended its emissions trading scheme to include aviation.
 Airlines have been receiving annual tradable allowances covering a certain
 level of emissions.
 Any shortfall between the allocated sum of free emissions allowances and
 their actual emissions require the purchase of additional allowances.
 Initially, all flights arriving in or departing from an airport in the
 EU were included.
 The 'equivalent measures policy' set out in the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "EU directive 2008/101/EC"
target "https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=celex%3A32008L0101"

\end_inset

 promised that whenever 'a third country adopts measures, which have an
 environmental effect at least equivalent to that of this Directive', flights
 from that country arriving in the EU would be exempted from obligations
 to be covered with emission permits.
 The directive stated that 'the Community scheme may serve as a model' and
 that member states should 'encourage third countries to take equivalent
 measures'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, states such as the US, China, India, Russia and Saudi Arabia opposed
 the scheme and partly prohibited their airlines from complying with it
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Murphy et al 2016"
target "https://www.transportenvironment.org/sites/te/files/2016_09_Aviation_ETS_gaining_altitude.pdf"

\end_inset

).
 In response to this opposition, the EU modified after only one year (in
 November 2012) the system to a ‘reduced scope’, which means that only flights
 between and within EU member states are included.
 This ‘stop-the-clock’ approach is temporary and if no new decision is made,
 ‘full scope’ will start again in 2024 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "(Larsson et al 2018)"
target "https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/14693062.2018.1562871"

\end_inset

, meaning that as in 2012 all flights arriving or departing in an EU country
 would again be covered.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The CORSIA treaty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2016, the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) adopted a
 global scheme requiring airline operators to offset increases in carbon
 dioxide emissions from international flights above the aggregate emissions
 in 2020.
 It is called CORSIA, which stands for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Carbon Offsetting and Reduction Scheme For International Aviation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The offset obligations only apply to flights between participating countries.
 A major point of contention in the negotiations has been and continues
 to be the choice of eligibility criteria for the carbon offsets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "elibility conditions "
target "https://carbonmarketwatch.org/publications/31111/"

\end_inset

for offsets will affect which type of projects will get funded.
 One example of possible offset programs that could be accepted are the
 Forest Carbon Partnership Facility's offsets for reduced tropical deforestation.
 Another is the Clean Development Mechanims (CDM), which has evolved to
 now finance mostly renewable energy projects in developing countries.
 Even once an offset category has been accepted, there remain crucial choices
 about vintage conditions.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Warnecke et al. (2019)"
target "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41558-019-0415-y"

\end_inset

 find that the CDM offset will be effective only if eligibility is limited
 to new projects or projects that are at risk of discontinuing greenhouse
 gas abatement without further support.
 Without such a restriction, they conclude, the offset demand from CORSIA
 would be met by projects that would continue anyway and the price for the
 offsets per ton of CO2 would drop below $1.
 Fearing that the standards that end up being chosen will be very lax and,
 France, the Netherlands, Portugal, Belgium, Austria, Finland and Norway
 have threatened independently to withdraw from the agreement if the offset
 eligibility standards are not chosen stringent enough.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on these concerns of a dilution of the level of ambition of CORSIA,
 the EU has kept open the possibility of taking unilateral measures to increase
 carbon pricing on international aviation.
 As mentioned in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-EU's-unilateral"

\end_inset

, by default, all flights to and from EU countries will again be included
 in the EU emissions trading scheme in 2024.
 The EU appears to also be open to alternative mechanisms, as it held a
 public consultation in 2016 on the question.
 In the next section we will build on suggestions made in response to this
 consultation.
 Based on the suggestion we will define a proposal for a club mechanism
 for taxing international aviation emissions and financing a global public
 good institution for climate change mitigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:The-CORSIA+-proposal"

\end_inset

The CORSIA+ proposal (based on common suggestions made in the EU's public
 consultation in 2016)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2016 the EU held a '
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "consultation"
target "https://ec.europa.eu/clima/sites/clima/files/docs/0029/registered_en.pdf"

\end_inset

 on market-based measures to reduce the climate change impact from international
 aviation'.
 In response to this consultation a common suggestion was that the EU should
 price carbon emissions from all flights, either by reinstating the ETS
 with full scope and with 'equivalent measures policies' as it did in 2012
 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-EU's-unilateral"

\end_inset

), or by introducing analogous carbon taxes 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "France, the Netherlands and Belgium"
target "https://www.aviation24.be/airlines/along-with-france-and-the-netherlands-belgium-wants-europe-to-tax-air-travel/"

\end_inset

have also recently argued for such European carbon taxes
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A second important suggestion was that this time the EU countries should
 not keep all the money from the permit auctions (or the tax revenue) for
 themselves but instead allocate at least a proportion of it to the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Green Climate Fund"
target "https://www.greenclimate.fund/home"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CORSIA+ proposal defined below extends these suggestions into a club
 mechanism.
 The countries initiating such a club would agree on an Global Public Good
 Institution for climate change mitigation for which money will be raised
 through the mechanism.
 By the term 'Global Public Good Institution' (GPGIs) we shall mean any
 global institution that uses money to cause increases in the provision
 of a specified global public good.
 The 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Green Climate Fund"
target "https://www.greenclimate.fund/home"

\end_inset

 fits this definition, since it uses its money for climate change mitigation.
 Another example of a GPGI for climate change mitigation is any fund that
 uses its available money to buy up carbon offset certificates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Proposal 1: The CORSIA+ mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CORSIA+ mechanism for a given GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 for climate change mitigation defines a club through the following two
 obligations that participating countries have to comply with
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Throughout this article we will define all mechanisms in terms of taxes.
 However, one can restate each of them in a way that allows countries to
 use emissions trading schemes instead of taxes to put a price on emissions
 and to raise revenue from permit auctions instead of from taxes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) (
\series bold
the taxation obligation
\series default
s) Each participating country 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in Participants$
\end_inset

 is required to levy a tax with rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on carbon emissions from all outgoing international flights and also on
 incoming international flights arriving from countries that do not participate.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This condition 1 corresponds to the EU's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equivalent measures policy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from 2012 explained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-EU's-unilateral"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2) (
\series bold
the allocation obligation
\series default
s) Each participating country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 must allocate a proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $1-r$
\end_inset

 of the tax revenue that it collects to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 It can retain the remaining proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 for itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
An illustration of the taxation obligation for participants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following diagram illustrates the taxation obligation for participants.
 Depicted is the case of a hypothetical world consisting of four countries
 at the strategy profile where country 1 and 2 participate whilst country
 3 and 4 do not:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/DELL/Downloads/taxationrulesparticipants.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here the green strokes near country 1 indicate the flights that country
 1 is obliged to tax and similarly for country 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The effects of the retention rate parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose all countries participate and we decrease 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 Then we cause money that otherwise would accrue to the governments to instead
 go to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 for climate change mitigation.
 Due to the public good nature of climate change mitigation, we should expect
 global welfare to increase.
 Thus, setting aside considerations about participation incentives, we should
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, to create sufficient participation incentives we might need to
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 quite high.
 This is in fact what we will find in the numerical simulations using the
 model that will be defined in the next section.
 In the simulations reported in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Numerical-simulations"

\end_inset

 we will need to set 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 at least at 0.4 to get any participation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\emph on
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:A-model-1"

\end_inset

The model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The world is assumed to be partitioned into the 12 blocks of the RICE model
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "(Nordhaus 2010)"
target "https://www.icpsr.umich.edu/icpsrweb/ICPSR/studies/28461#"

\end_inset

, each of which is assumed to behave as a single player: Africa, China,
 EU, Eurasia, India, Japan, Latin America, Middle East, Other high income
 countries, Russia, other Asia.
 The payoff of each these players is assumed to be the sum of the payoffs
 of the countries that it comprises.
 Moreover, we shall assume that country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's utility is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{i}=t_{i}-c_{i}xF_{i}+Y_{i}+b_{i}xG+\theta_{s}^{i}Z_{s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "(1)"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For ease of exposition we have written here the payoff in the context of
 the CORSIA+ mechanism and assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is small.
 The payoff is relative to a situation without the CORSIA+ mechanism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the transfer that country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 receives, i.e.
 the money that it can retain from the tax revenue collected if country
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 participates.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes the aggregate emissions from international flights from or to country
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 whose emissions are taxed as a result of the mechanism.
 Denoting by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}$
\end_inset

 the emissions from flights from 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}=\sum_{j\in I}f_{ij}+f_{ji}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 participates (where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 denotes the set of all countries) and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}=\sum_{j\in Participants}f_{ij}+f_{ji}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 does not participate.
 
\begin_inset Formula $xF_{i}$
\end_inset

 is thus the aggregate tax revenue from taxes on flights arriving at or
 departing from country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, collected due to the CORSIA+ mechanism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 measures how country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 evaluates the burden associated with the taxation its flights are subject
 to.
 We model it as having two components: 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=\sigma_{i}+\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 accounts for the welfare effect that country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 internalises, which is due to the incidence of the taxes born by its citizens
 and the potential deadweight loss that they incur.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 captures redistributive effects between countries.
 One such redistributive effect is that when a country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 increases its aviation taxes some tourists switch to travelling to a different
 country 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 instead and thereby rents from these tourists acrue to country 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 instead of to country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Keen and Strand (2012)"
target "http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/678661468155734989/pdf/WPS5950.pdf"

\end_inset

highlight another redistributive effect, namely a terms of trade effect:
 When one country increases its aviation taxes, the world market prices
 for tourism services increase.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Symmetrically, when aviation taxes are charged on flights that are neither
 to nor from country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, there are redistributive effects in favor of country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 We capture these effects in the term 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We will assume linear separability of all these effects.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For small values of the tax rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 the additive separability that we are assuming will approximately be correct.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Formally, we will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}=\sum_{j\neq i,l\neq i:j\,or\,l\,participate}\gamma_{ijl}xf_{jl}$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 gives the rents from tourism that are shifted to country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as a result of each dollar of taxes that are imposed on flights from country
 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 to country 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Estimates-of-Payoffs"

\end_inset

 we will make assumptions about the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i,}\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ijl}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It could be useful to extend the model to one in which the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i,}\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 are derived from consumer preferences and the production structure.
 In this case we would endogenously obtain the dependence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i,}\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and we could compute the welfare maximising 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,r)$
\end_inset

 for the CORSIA+ mechanism.
 Then we could similarly compute the maximal welfare that the other mechanisms
 explained below in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Definitions-of-the"

\end_inset

 can generate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
However, we will instead assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is small and fixed.
 Since the alternative proposed mechanisms defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Definitions-of-the"

\end_inset

 have an analogous retention rate parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, we will compare the mechanisms for the entire interval [0,1] of values
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 can take.
 It will turn out that as far the welfare achieved is concerned, the ranking
 of the mechanisms is the same for all relevant 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 We will argue in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Overall-comparison-of"

\end_inset

 that it is plausible that this ranking also does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $G:=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i\in I}F_{i}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 is the total tax revenue that is collected due to the MGF mechanism.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 measures the net benefits that country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 perceives due to the reduction in emissions caused by the carbon taxes
 levied on the flights.
 This includes two effects: firstly, the reduction in climate change and
 secondly the reduction in the world market price of oil that is caused
 by the reduction in the demand for oil from the aviation industry.
 We will estimate these effects in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-global-effects"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the total money raised for the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{s}$
\end_inset

 depends on the strategies chosen by the players.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{s}^{i}$
\end_inset

 are constants that correspond to how country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 values a dollar going to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation (1) applies for the case of the CORSIA+ mechanism, where a single
 GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is selected for being financed via the mechanism.
 In the alternative mechanisms defined in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Definitions-of-the"

\end_inset

, there is not just one but a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of GPGIs that will financed .
 In this case country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's payoff becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{i}=t_{i}-c_{i}xF_{i}+Y_{i}+b_{i}xG+\sum_{s\in S}\theta_{s}^{i}Z_{s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the numerical simulations we will assume that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 consists of the 6 GPGIs listed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "2 GPGIs"

\end_inset

.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Effects-of-the"

\end_inset

 we will compute values for the various parameters, using econometric estimates
 and data when possible, whilst resorting to ad hoc numerical assumptions
 for several of the parameters.
 Then we will simulate the unfolding of the game using an iterated best
 response algorithm in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Numerical-simulations"

\end_inset

.
 Before doing this, we will in the next section motivate and define the
 three alternative proposals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\emph on
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "3 sec: The-Multiple-Cause"

\end_inset


\emph default
Three new proposals for club mechanisms to raise money for multiple global
 public good institutions from taxes on aviation emissions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As already pointed out, in the choice of the retention rate parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 for the CORSIA+ mechanism there is a fundamental trade-off between achieving
 strong participation incentives and efficiency: Increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is good for increasing participation incentives but it comes at a welfare
 cost due to the decrease in the amount of money raised for GPGIs.
 Under the numerical assumptions detailed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Estimates-of-Payoffs"

\end_inset

 it turns out that if 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is less than 39%, there is a unique Nash equilibrium, namely the profile
 where no player participates.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $r>39\%$
\end_inset

 there is a Nash equilibrium with full participation.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For ease of exposition we report in these motivating paragraphs results
 about what Nash equilibria exist.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Numerical-simulations"

\end_inset

 we will instead report the results obtained using an iterated best response
 algorithm, which allows us to evaluate the different mechanisms taking
 into account not only which Nash equilibria exist but also how difficult
 or easy it is to reach them.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus CORSIA+ can raise at most 61% of the tax revenue collected for the
 GPGI that it finances.
 The question therefore arises as to whether we could design alternative
 mechanisms that could raise a greater proportion of the tax revenue collected
 for GPGIs.
 The three proposals that we will define are partly motivated by this question
 and answer it in the affirmative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The three proposals build on CORSIA+ by keeping the taxation obligation
 unchanged.
 However, in these alternative mechanisms the allocation obligation will
 be different.
 Participating countries get the option to decide on the GPGIs to which
 to allocate the money that they collect if they renounce on the right to
 retain any of the money for themselves.
 Reflecting this feature, we call the proposals 
\series bold
MGF Mechanisms,
\series default
 for '
\series bold
M
\series default
ultiple 
\series bold
G
\series default
lobal public good institutions 
\series bold
F
\series default
inancing 
\series bold
Mechanisms
\series default
'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast to CORSIA and CORSIA+, the treaty that would establish the MGF
 mechanisms would not select just a single GPGI to be financed through the
 mechanism.
 Instead, it would fix a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of GPGIs.
 The participating countries that give up the right to retain any of the
 tax revenue that they collect would be able to allocate the tax revenue
 that they collect to the GPGIs from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 For the numerical simulations we will assume that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is given by the 6 GPGIs listed in the next subsection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "2 GPGIs"

\end_inset

Global Public Good Institutions (GPGIs): 6 examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall mean by a 'Global Public Good Institution' (GPGI) any institution
 that uses money to cause increases in the provision of a particular global
 public good that it is dedicated to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Fund to buy up Emission Reduction Certificates from the Clean Development
 Mechanism (CDM) (existing since 2008)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CDM is the largest carbon offsetting programme available at present.
 It was established under the Kyoto Protocol.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
CEPI (The Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovation) (existing since
 2017)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "CEPI"
target "http://www.cepi.org/"

\end_inset

 has so far mostly been focussing on advancing vaccines against known threats.
 Recently, it has started to also fund new platform technologies with the
 potential to accelerate the development and manufacture of vaccines against
 previously unknown pathogens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, TB and Malaria (existing since 2002)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
This GPGI allocates funding for programs against AIDS, TB and Malaria.
 Allocations made to countries are 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "proportional"
target "https://www.theglobalfund.org/media/5642/fundingmodel_allocations2017-2019detailedexplanation_report_en.pdf?u=636898879780000000"

\end_inset

 to the disease burden for each of the three diseases and to an index of
 economic capacity calculated based on per capita GDP.
 The Global Fund works closely together with another GPGI, called UNITAID,
 which has been financed through 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "ticket taxes"
target "http://www.leadinggroup.org/rubrique177.html"

\end_inset

 on international flights since 2006.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "FCCP: The-Forest-Carbon"

\end_inset

 (existing since 2011)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
This 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Fund"
target "https://www.forestcarbonpartnership.org/carbon-fund-0"

\end_inset

 rewards countries with tropical forest as a function of the policies they
 pursue to conserve their tropical forests.
 In the future this institution will also condition its payments on results
 (amount of tropical forests conserved), as Norway already does in bilateral
 contracts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
ITER (The International Thermonuclear Reactor) (existing since 2007)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "ITER"
target "https://www.iter.org/"

\end_inset

is an international nuclear fusion research and engineering megaproject.
 Its stated goal is to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

demonstrate the scientific and technological feasibility of fusion energy
 for peaceful use
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Carbon Pricing Reward Fund (proposed)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This Fund would reward countries as a function of their emissions, their
 carbon tax revenue collected and their fossil fuel subsidies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A preview of the estimates for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}^{s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following diagram shows the results that we obtain in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Effects-of-the"

\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in k}\theta_{i}^{s}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in K=$
\end_inset

{Africa, China, EU, Eurasia, India, Japan, Latin America, Middle East, Other
 high income countries, Russia, other Asia} and for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S=\{CDM,CEPI,Global\,Fund,\,Forest\,Carbon\,Partnership's\,Carbon\,Fund,\,ITER,\,Carbon\,Pricing\,Reward\,Fund\}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename c75with9participants/payoffs.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We arrive at these numbers using econometric estimates, data and several
 ad hoc assumptions.
 The methods are fully described in in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Effects-of-the"

\end_inset

.
 However, without going into much detail, we can already provide some explanatio
ns of these payoff estimates: Africa most benefits from Global Fund, since
 two thirds of the Global Fund's disbursements are made to African countries.
 China benefits substantially from all the GPGIs that reduce fossil fuel
 use: {CDM, ITER, Carbon Pricing Reward Fund}.
 The reasons for this are two-fold: Firstly through the reduced climate
 change and secondly through the decrease in the world market oil price
 that is caused by the decrease in fossil fuel demand.
 The latter effect is significant for China, since it imports most of its
 oil.
 The Carbon Pricing Reward Fund has a particular strong effect on the world
 market oil price, since it would mostly reduce oil use, in contrast to
 the CDM, which will mostly reduce coal use.
 The EU has a similar profile of payoffs to that from China, just larger
 in scale, given that the EU's economy is larger.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gains for the oil importers from reduced oil use and thus reduced world
 market oil prices come at the expense of oil exporters.
 This is why the Middle East negatively values money going to the three
 GPGIs that reduce fossil fuel use.
 It values particularly neagitvely money going to the Carbon Pricing, since
 this will disproportioately reduce demand for oil.
 Eurasia's payoff profile is qualitatively similar but much smaller in absolute
 value, since Eurasia is a much smaller player overall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
India and 'other Asia' both greatly benefit from any dollar going to the
 Carbon Pricing Reward Fund.
 This is in part because of the reduced climate damages and the reduced
 world market oil price that result from additional dollars going to the
 Carbon Pricing Reward Fund.
 In addition to that, the two players receive reward payments for low per
 capita emisssions and low fossil fuel subsidies from this GPGI and will
 thereby reap informational rents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Latin America benefits greatly from money going to the Forest Carbon Partnership
's Carbon Fund.
 This GPGI rewards countries for conserving tropical forests.
 Since conservation costs are countries' private information, they reap
 informational rents.
 Latin America, possessing a large fraction of the world's tropical forests,
 will reap a large part of these informational rents.
 Other Asia and Africa also value a dollar going the Forest Carbon Partnership's
 Carbon Fund, again mainly because of the informational rents that they
 get from it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarise: There appear to be three major effects determining the payoffs
 countries derive from additional money being provided to GPGIs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) effects due to the provision of the global public good
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2) redistributional effects due to induced price changes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3) informational rents
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of these three effects turn out to be heterogenous across countries
 and as a result our payoff estimates (which take into account these three
 effects) exhibit substantial heterogeneity across countries.
 The two mechanism that we will now define are motivated by the hope that
 it might be possible to harness this heterogeity to generate participation
 incentives that arise as participants will be able to affect the allocation
 of money across GPGIs (in ways determined by the rules of the respective
 mechanisms).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Definitions-of-the"

\end_inset

Definitions of the two MGF mechanisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now define two new proposals for club mechanisms.
 We shall call the proposals 
\series bold
MGF Mechanisms
\series default
 for '
\series bold
M
\series default
ultiple 
\series bold
G
\series default
lobal public good institutions 
\series bold
F
\series default
inancing 
\series bold
Mechanisms
\series default
'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Definition-of-Proposal 1"

\end_inset

Definition of Proposal 2: The Simple MGF mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Simple MGF mechanism defines a club which any country can join or quit
 at any point in time.
 It could be started by any initial subset of countries who would select
 a set
\emph on
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\emph default
 of
\emph on
 GPGIs
\emph default

\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Throughout this article we take 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to be exogenous.
 A fully worked-out proposal would need to specify rules for how the set
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 could be modified over time.
 One posssible procedure would be the following: Participating countries
 could propose that a GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 be added to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then all participating countries would cast a vote.
 These votes could be weighted by population size.
 The GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 would be added to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 iff the set of participants voting for the addition of the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 comprises at least 50% of the weight of the set of all participants.
 Alternatively, the weight given to a country could be the sum of its population
 and some (country-independent) coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 times the aggregate voluntary contributions made by this country to all
 GPGIs in the 5 years preceding the vote.
 This would enhance countries' incentives to make voluntary contributions
 to GPGIs (including not only the GPGIs in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 but any GPGI recognized as such by some independent commission).
 Thereby, countries could create new GPGIs through voluntary contributions,
 knowing that if they perform sufficiently well to attract wide support,
 it will be added to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and could receive future funding via the MGF mechanism.
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 could be set so that at the time of the introduction of the MGF mechanism
 half of the aggregate weight of the worlds' countries would be due to the
 population and half of their aggregate weight would be due to the voluntary
 contributions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that would be considered as 
\emph on
eligible
\emph default
 for being financed through the mechanism in a way made precise in the definitio
ns that follow below.
 We denote the set of all countries by 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and the set of all participants to the MGF mechanism by 
\begin_inset Formula $Participants$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The Simple MGF mechanism for the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of GPGIs and the retention rate parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 defines a club through the following two obligations that participating
 countries have to comply with:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
1) (
\series bold
the taxation obligation
\series default
) Each participating country 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in Participants$
\end_inset

 is required to levy a tax with rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on carbon emissions from all outgoing international flights and also on
 incoming international flights arriving from countries that do not participate.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Condition 1 is similar to the EU's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equivalent measures
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 policy implemented during 2012 based on the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "EU directive 2008/101/EC"
target "https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=celex%3A32008L0101"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
2) (
\series bold
the allocation obligation
\series default
) As a result of implementing the taxation obligation, each participating
 country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 collects a certain amount 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}$
\end_inset

 of tax revenue.
 The country can decide on the propotion 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}$
\end_inset

 that it wants to allocate to GPGIs.
 It can allocate the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}M_{i}$
\end_inset

 in any way to the GPGIs from the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of eligible GPGIs.
 Of the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-p_{i})M_{i}$
\end_inset

 that country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 does not allocate to GPGIs, it can retain the proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 (which is the retention rate parameter of the mechanism).
 The remaining amount, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-r)(1-p_{i})M_{i}$
\end_inset

 is added to the GPGIs proportionally to the aggregate contributions made
 to them via the mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For ease of exposition we have stated the definition here in a static way.
 In fact, countries could continually adjust their actions over time.
 In practice, the rules that we have set out could here could be applied
 each month.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To clarify the definition, we now restate it with some notation.
 For the purposes of this article we consider the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of eligible GPGIs and the retention rate parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 to be design choices for the mechanism.
 We take them to be fixed, i.e.
 we do not allow players to affect them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As introduced in the definition, we shall denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{k}$
\end_inset

 the flow of tax revenue that a participating country collects by taxing
 in accordance with the taxation obligation.
 Each participant has to choose the proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 that he wants to allocate to GPGIs.
 He also has to choose how to distribute the flow of money 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}M_{i}$
\end_inset

 to the GPGIs.
 In other words, he has to choose numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{s}^{i}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{s\in S}q_{s}^{i}=1$
\end_inset

 and thereby he allocates the flow 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{s}^{i}p_{i}M_{i}$
\end_inset

 to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 These flows of moneys going to the GPGIs we will call the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direct allocations to the GPGIs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Of the money 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-p_{i})M_{i}$
\end_inset

 that country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 does not allocate, he retains the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $r(1-p_{i})M_{i}$
\end_inset

 for himself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amount of money 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in Participants}(1-r)(1-p_{i})M_{i}$
\end_inset

 is neither given as direct allocations to GPGIs nor retained by participants.
 The definition of the mechanism stipulates that this money is to be allocated
 to the GPGIs in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in proportion to the aggregate direct allocations made to these GPGIs via
 the mechanism.
 In other words, from the money 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in Participants}(1-r)(1-p_{i})M_{i}$
\end_inset

 the following amount is allocated to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\sum_{i\in Participants}q_{s}^{i}p_{i}M_{i}}{\sum_{s\in S}\sum_{i\in Participant}q_{s}^{i}p_{i}M_{i}}\sum_{i\in Participants}(1-r)(1-p_{i})M_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This concludes the definition of the mechanism.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Actually, there is one case that we did not cover in the definition so far:
 What if all participants choose 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 if no participant makes any direct allocation to the GPGIs? The details
 of how we define the rules for this case turn out to be unimportant.
 Here is the definition that was used for the numerical simulations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Numerical-simulations"

\end_inset

: If all countries choose 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 then each country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 can allocate the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-r)M_{i}$
\end_inset

 to the GPGIs.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, we can write the strategy space for country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\text{A_{i}=\{'not\,participate'}\}\text{∪}\{p_{i}:p_{i}\in[0,1]\}\times\{q^{i}\in[0,1]^{S}:\sum_{s\in S}q_{s}^{i}=1\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To further illustrate the definition, let us compute the flow of tax revenue
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}$
\end_inset

 that a participating country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 ends up collecting.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\text{ik}}$
\end_inset

 the carbon emissions from international flights from country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to country 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and as before.
 We have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{i}=x(\sum_{k\in Participants}f_{\text{ik}}+\sum_{k\in I\backslash Participants}(f_{\text{ik}}+f_{\text{ki}}))
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A graphical representation of the definition of the Simple MGF mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MGF mechanism is defined for countries, each of which can decide whether
 or not to participate and if so, how to participate.
 However, for the simulations in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Numerical-simulations"

\end_inset

 we will follow the common practice (see e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Nordhaus (2015)"
target "http://econ.sciences-po.fr/sites/default/files/file/Climate%20Clubs%3A%20Overcoming%20Free-riding%20in%20International%20Climate%20Policy%20-%20aer.15000001.pdf"

\end_inset

) of assuming that countries coalesce in blocks, each of which acts as a
 single player, as we have already stated in the description of the model
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:A-model-1"

\end_inset

.
 Depicted in the diagram below is a Nash equilibrium is strategy profile
 obtained in these simulations for the Simple MGF mechanism.
 The diagram describes how the final allocations to GPGIs are generated,
 given the players' strategy profile:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\noindent
\align left
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MGF/seminar presentation/diagramatic computations for Simple MGF (2) final 2.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 40
	clip

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the top of the diagram are displayed the design choices for the mechanism:
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of eligible GPGIs is here taken to be the 6 GPGIs described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "2 GPGIs"

\end_inset

.
 The retention rate parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is set to equal 0.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first line gives the design choices for the mechanism (i.e.
 the set of eligible GPGIs and the retention rate parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

).
 In the illustrative example represented by the diagram the set of eligible
 GPGIs has only three elements: CEPI, a Fund to purchase CDM offsets and
 the Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund.
 (For the actual simulations we will take 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to be the set of the 6 GPGIs that we described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "2 GPGIs"

\end_inset

).
 Below these design choices we depict with the white rectangles the tax
 revenues that the participating players collect.
 These collected tax revenues only depend on which players are participating,
 since the taxation obligation is the same for all participants, irrespective
 of how they participate.
 Below that we have shown an example of a strategy profile.
 The players that have colored their rectangle are those that have chosen
 to participate with right to allocate.
 (We have arranged them to all be on the left to make the diagram more readable.)
 The colors correspond to the different GPGIs.
 Thus players 1 and 3 have chosen to give all to CEPI (in blue), player
 4 gives all to the Fund to purchase carbon offsets from the Clean Development
 Mechanism and players 2 and 5 give all to the Forest Carbon Partnership's
 Carbon Fund.
 Players 6 to 8 have chosen to participate without the right to allocate.
 A proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

 of each of these players' rectangle is black, corresponding to the money
 that they can retain.
 The remaining part of their rectangles is made grey.
 These grey parts are collected and summed together below on the left.
 In the bottom left corner of the diagram we also collect and sum together
 the direct allocations for each GPGI.
 The final allocations are obtained through the computational step indicated
 by the arrow: It consists of converting the grey rectangle into colored
 parts in proportion to the direct allocations to the different GPGIs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To explore the consequence of the definition of the Simple MGF mechanism,
 consider for a moment what would happen if player 5 was to switch to participat
e without the right to allocate.
 In that case, he would be able to retain 
\begin_inset Formula $r*4=\frac{1}{4}*4=1$
\end_inset

 units of the tax revenue that he collects.
 However, the remaining 3 units of the tax revenue that he collects would
 now be split over the three GPGIs in propotion to the others' direct allocation
s.
 Moreover, the 10 grey units of revenue that come from those who already
 participate without the right to allocate will now be allocated in greater
 proportion to blue (i.e.
 CEPI) and green (i.e.
 CDM) and in lesser proportion to red (i.e.
 the Forest Carbon Partnership's carbon fund).
 If player 5 prefers red sufficiently strongly over blue and green, he will
 prefer to participate with right to allocate instead of participating without
 right to allocate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question arises as to whether there exist modifications of the Simple
 MGF mechanism that would further enhance the incentives to participate
 with the right to allocate without complexifying the mechanism too much.
 The proposals 3 and 4 given below are attempts to achieve exactly that.
 They could also remedy an allocative inefficiency that might arise with
 the Simple MGF which we shall now briefly illustrate: Suppose there is
 a GPGI that no player ranks highest but that all players value highly.
 Then in the simple MGF mechanism this GPGI might not receive any money,
 even if the global marginal payoff from an additional dollar going to this
 GPGI is higher than that for all of the other GPGIs.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Brandl et al. (2019)"
target "https://www.google.com/url?q=http://dss.in.tum.de/files/brandt-research/donate.pdf&source=gmail&ust=1558388068489000&usg=AFQjCNFj35CyAX-DfVCMw17kxFOsO_hRiw"

\end_inset

propose alternative mechanisms to mitigate this inefficiency.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The proposals 3 and 4 can at least partly remedy this inefficiency, as
 we will see.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Definition-of-Proposal 3-1"

\end_inset

Definition of Proposal 3: The MGF mechanism with Proportional Matching Funds
 (PMFs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of the 'MGF mechanism with Proportional Matching Funds' is
 obtained by adding a further class of institutions to which those participating
 and choosing option 1 can allocate the tax revenue that they collect.
 In other words: The taxation obligations for participants are identical
 to those in the Simple MGF Mechanism and the allocation obligations are
 modified by expanding the set of institutions to which the participants
 can make direct allocations to also include 'Proportional Matching Funds'
 (PMFs)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An analogous institution already exists in the realm of private philantrhopy,
 where it is sometimes also called 'Proportional Matching Fund' and sometimes
 called 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Incentive Fund"
target "https://www.globalgiving.org/2018-GivingTuesday-Campaign-/"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 .
 Each country participating with the right to allocate can make direct allocatio
ns to the GPGIs (we will refer to the money allocated this ways as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direct allocations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 However, the country can also give money to the PMFs.
 A PMF is defined by the set of GPGIs that it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

supports
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The money that the PMF receives is allocated to these GPGIs in proportion
 to the direct allocations made to them through the mechanism
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
i.e.
 other contributions such as voluntary contributions by states or foundations
 are not taken into account
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 As a result, the money in the PMFs enhances the effects that direct allocations
 to the GPGIs will have: The greater the direct allocations made to a GPGI
 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

, the more money from the PMFs supporting 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 will we be allocated to 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Thus participation incentives for those strongly favoring one GPGI over
 the other GPGIs are increased.
 This strategic benefit suggests that for reaching wide participation it
 might be good to incentivise players to give to PMFs.
 In the definition given below this is achieved by adding the grey money
 (coming from the participants without the right to allocate) to the PMFs.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If players act with foresight, then they might want to give to PMFs even
 if the grey money was not given to the PMFs.
 However, we will assume in the simulations that players act myopically.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before stating a fully general formal definition for the MGF Mechanism with
   Proportional Matching Funds, we will illustrate it with the aid of the
 following diagram:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MGF/seminar presentation/diagramatic computations for HPMF final version 5 (2).png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 40
	clip

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here player 1 participates with the right to allocate and gives all the
 money he collects to the PMF (  Proportional Matching Fund) for blue and
 green (i.e.
 for CEPI and for the Fund to purchase carbon offset from the Clean Development
 Mechanism).
 Player 2 participates with the right to allocate and gives all the money
 he collects to the PMF for green and red (i.e.
 for the Fund to purchase carbon offset from the Clean Development Mechanism
 and for the Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund).
 Players 3,4 and 5 give all the tax revenue as direct allocations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the bottom left corner we collect all the direct allocations to the GPGIs.
 Above that we collect all the direct allocations to the PMFs.
 Above that, we gather all the money (in grey) that is collected by those
 who participate without the right to allocate and that is not retained
 by them.
 The arrows indicate the steps through which the final allocations are computed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first step, the grey money is distributed to the PMFs in proportion
 to the direct allocations made to the PMFs.
 Graphically, this first step is represented by the first arrow.
 It consists of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

converting the grey money into PMF money, in proportion to the direct allocation
s made to the PMFs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 To state the rules for this first computation step formally and in full
 generality, let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 the aggregate amount of money that is not allocated (i.e.
 the amount in grey in the diagram).
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subset S$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|J|\geq2$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $|J|$
\end_inset

 denotes the number of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{J}$
\end_inset

 denote the aggregate direct allocations to the PMF for 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

.
 Then from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 the following amount is given to the PMF for 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{|J|H_{J}}{\sum_{K\subset S:|K|\geq2}|K|H_{K}}G$
\end_inset

.
 The rationale motivating this rule is that the larger the set 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 of GPGIs that a player supports by giving to the 
\begin_inset Formula $HPMF_{J}$
\end_inset

, the more say he effectively leaves to the other participants.
 As a result, this can increase the incentives for the other players to
 join.
 It makes sense to reward the player for this, which is achieved through
 the simple weighting rule implemented by the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{|J|H_{J}}{\sum_{K\subset S:|K|\geq2}|K|H_{K}}G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second step (represented by the second arrow from the left), these
 amounts are added to the direct allocations to the PMFs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the third (and last
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We could have added a fourth step, where we would for each GPGI add up all
 the money ending up going to it.
 From a fully rational point of view, these aggregate final allocations
 should be all that matter.
 However, in the diagram as it is we emphasize the tracability of the money
 that is ensured in the mechanism by construction.
 This might actually be an attractive feature of the mechanism.
 It is in contrast to other mechanisms such as normalised gradient addition
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "(Benjamin et al 2017)"
target "https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11127-017-0414-3"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

) step each PMF distributes its money to the GPGIs it supports, in proportion
 to the direct allocations made to these GPGIs.
 In particular each PMFs takes into account only the direct allocations
 to the GPGIs and not the allocations made by the other PMFs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To help clarify the definition, we can write the strategy space for player
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\text{A_{i}=\{'not\,participate'}\}\text{∪}\{p_{i}:p_{i}\in[0,1]\}\times\{q^{i}\in[0,1]^{\mathbb{P}(S)-\emptyset}:\sum_{J\in\mathbb{P}(S)-\emptyset}q_{J}^{i}=1\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}(S)-\emptyset$
\end_inset

 is the set of all non-empty subsets of the GPGIs.
 The interpretation is that for 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in S$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}^{\{j\}}$
\end_inset

 is the proportion of player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's tax revenue that he allocates directly to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and for a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subset S$
\end_inset

 with at least two elements, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}^{J}$
\end_inset

 is the proportion of player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's tax revenue that he allocates directly to the 
\begin_inset Formula $HPMF_{J}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Numerical-simulations"

\end_inset

Numerical simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each of the proposed mechanisms we want to predict the outcome that
 would result if this mechanism was initiated by a given initial set of
 players.
 As the initial set of players we will first take the EU and China.
 Given the history of efforts for price aviation emissions sketeched in
 section...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-algorithm-used"

\end_inset

The iterated best response algorithm used
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with an initial set of participants.
 The initial action profile consists of each of the initial participants
 allocating all the tax revenue that they collect (by complying with the
 taxation obligation) to their most preferred GPGI.
 A random player is chosen and he is given the opportunity to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we draw at each step a random player who is given the opportunity to
 adjust his strategy to a best response.
 There are two phases in the algorithm.
 In the first phase the initial participants discard the option of quitting
 the mechanism.
 In other words, when they are given the opportunity to adjust their strategy,
 they pick the best one amongst all those strategies that involve participating
 in the mechanism.
 The algorithm runs until no player wants to adjust their strategy any more.
 Then the second phase of the algorithm begins.
 From then onwards the initial participants no longer take the option of
 quitting off the table.
 The algorithm is then run until no player wants to adjust their strategy
 any more, which means that a Nash equilibrium is reached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all the simulations run thus far, the algorithm always reached a Nash
 equilibrium, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $r\leq0.7$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0.7$
\end_inset

, however, the algorithm sometimes did not reach a Nash equilibrium for
 the MGF mechanism with PMFs.
 Instead, it appeared to jump around indefinitely in the space of strategy
 profiles.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is well known that iterated best response dynamics can fail to converge,
 even if there are pure strategy Nash equilibria (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Roughgarden 2013"
target "https://theory.stanford.edu/~tim/f13/l/l16.pdf"

\end_inset

).
 This is indeed the case here: For 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0.7$
\end_inset

 one can show that if all players participate, then no player has an incentive
 to quit.
 Since the set of strategies that entail participation is convex, there
 must therefore exist at least one Nash equilibrium with full participation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For these cases I used a modifed version of the algorithm, where at each
 step a small positive parameter, called 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

, was slightly increased.
 At each step, again a random player was given the opportunity to adjust
 his strategy.
 However, it was assumed that the player would only actually adjust his
 strategy if the gain in payoffs exceeds 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The algorithm terminates when no player adjusts his strategy anymore.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
At this point, a Epsilon-equilibrium is , by the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "definition"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epsilon-equilibrium"

\end_inset

 of this solution concept.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This algorithm always terminated already for relatively small values of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The motivation for this algorithm is that it seems a priori plausible that
 the players that would initiate the mechanism would have enough patience
 and foresight to not immediately quit the mechanism again.
 Instead, they are likely to at least wait and see whether other players
 want to join.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now report the results for the case where the retention rate parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is 0.2.
 This value is just chosen for purposes of illustration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Results for r=0.2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we report the results obtained for 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0.2$
\end_inset

 for the different mechanisms.
 The algorithm was run 20 times for each of the mechanisms.
 We report the probability estimates that we obtain from the sample frequencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Results for CORSIA+
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We always reach the strategy profile where no player participates, which
 is a Nash equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Results for the Simple MGF for r=0.2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We always reach the strategy profile where no player participates, which
 is a Nash equilibrium.
\end_layout

