\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-expected-global"

\end_inset

The expected global welfare achieved by the different mechanisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename c75with9participants/averageAggregatePayoffs.png
	scale 41

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We let the retention rate parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 range from 0 to 1 in steps of 0.05.
 For each of these values the iterated best response algorithm described
 in 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-algorithm-used"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 was run for each mechanism 20 times.
 It always terminated, which means that a Nash equilibrium was always reached.
 In appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "part:A-more-detailed"

\end_inset

 we provide detailed summaries of the results.
 Here we shall focus on the average aggregate payoffs, which gives us an
 estimate of the expected global welfare that is generated.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that the payoffs in the game are normalised so as to be 0 for all players
 if none participates, so the aggregate payoffs do indeed give us the welfare
 gain relative to the status quo.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As a normalisation, we set the tax revenue that would be collected if all
 players participate to 1.
 Thus in the following graph for example a value of 0.35 for the average
 aggregate payoffs means that the monetary value of the global welfare gains
 achieved through the mechanism equals 35% of the money that is collected
 as tax revenue if all players participate.
 In the graph we see that the main contribution to welfare comes from the
 money raised for GPGIs and only a small part comes from the mitigation
 benefits of reduced aviation emissions.
 To see this, one can look at the point where the retention rate parameter
 is 1.
 At that value, all players always participate but no money is raised for
 GPGIs.
 Thus the welfare is just equal to the climate change mitigation benefits
 from reduced aviation emissions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To evaluate the relative performance of the three mechanisms, consider first
 the case where if a mechanism is implemented, the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is chosen at the value that maximises expected global welfare.
 As one can see in the graph, this optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is 0.45 for the MGF mechanism with All-Encompassing Proportional Matching
 Funds and 0.5 for CORSIA+ and for the Simple MGF mechanism.
 Under this assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is always chosen optimally, we get the following results:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Simple MGF mechanism achieves 13% more welfare than CORSIA+ and raises
 38% more money for GPGIs than CORSIA+.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MGF mechanism with AEPMFs achieves 29% more welfare than CORSIA+ and
 raises 47% more money for GPGIs than CORSIA+.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us look at what happens if we relax the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is chosen exactly at the level that maximises global welfare.
 The graph suggests that this is likely to strenghten the conclusion that
 the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs performs best.
 Indeed, on the interval [0.35,0.55] the welfare achieved by the MGF mechanism
 with AEPMFs is almost as good as at the optimal retention rate parameter.
 CORSIA+ and the Simple MGF Mechanism are less robust to deviations of the
 retention rate parameter from its optimal value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Overall-comparison-of"

\end_inset

Overall comparison of the mechanisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overall design question is to choose the triplet 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,r,mechanism)$
\end_inset

 so as to maximise 
\begin_inset Formula $expected\,welfare(x,r,mechanism)$
\end_inset

.
 In this study we have investigated the comparative performance of the mechanism
s only for the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is small.
 Let us now consider how the mechanisms' performances would change as we
 increase 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 To rigorously answer this question we would need to fully specifiy a model
 of demand for air travel.
 For a small 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we could make in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-tax-burden"

\end_inset

 the assumption that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{c_{k}}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the costs that players bear due to increased taxes when
 joining do not depend on who else is already participating.
 For large 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 this might no longer be true.
 However, if we can neglect this effect, then we can see what would happen
 for higher 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by running our simulations simply with increased values for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{c_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, the higher the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the larger the deadweight loss from the perspective of the players due
 to the decreased flying of their citizens.
 In ongoing computations (available soon in an updated version of the article)
 we explore what happens if we multiply each 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{c_{k}}$
\end_inset

 by the same factor 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The results so far indicate that for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 ranging from 1 to 1.5 the the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs appears to continue
 to yield higher expected global welfare than CORSIA+ and the Simple MGF
 Mechanism for practically all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 Thus it appears that the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs robustly outperforms
 CORSIA+ and the Simple MGF mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "part:A-more-detailed"

\end_inset

A more detailed summary of the simulation results for the different mechanisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Overview of results for r ranging from 0 to 1 for each mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now provide some summaries of the results that were obtained by letting
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 range from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 1 in steps of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.05$
\end_inset

.
 For each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 the algorithm (from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-algorithm-used"

\end_inset

) was run 20 times for each of 'CORSIA+', 'Simple MGF' and 'MGF with All-Encompa
ssing Proportional Matching Funds'.
 Let us denote by 'the eventual strategy profile reached under the algorithm'
 the last strategy profile that is recorded.
 This was always a Nash equilibrium for all of our simulations.
 The summary statistics displayed in the graphs are computed for the eventual
 strategy profiles over all the runs of the algorithm.
 For clarification, we provide the following descriptions of the computations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
'maximal aggregate payoffs': For each run of the algorithm we take the eventual
 strategy profile, compute the corresponding payoffs and sum them together.
 Then we take the maximal value amongst all runs of the algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
'average aggregate payoffs': For each run of the algorithm we take the eventual
 strategy profile, compute the corresponding payoffs and sum them together.
 Then we average over all runs of the algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
'maximal aggregate money raised for GPGIs': For each run of the algorithm
 we take the eventual strategy profile, compute the corresponding payoffs
 and sum them together.
 Then we take the maximal value amongst all runs of the algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
'average aggregate money raised for GPGIs': For each run of the algorithm
 we take the eventual strategy profile, compute the corresponding allocations
 to the GPGIs and sum them together.
 Then we average over all runs of the algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
'proportion of money collected that is raised for GPGIs': For each run of
 the algorithm we take the eventual strategy profile, compute the corresponding
 allocations to the GPGIs and sum them together.
 Then we average over all runs of the algorithm, thus obtaining the average
 money raised for GPGIs.
 Moreover, for each run of the algorithm we take the eventual strategy profile,
 compute the corresponding aggregate tax revenue raised.
 Then we average over all runs of the algorithm, thus obtaining the average
 tax revenue collected.
 Finally, we compute the ratio of the average money raised for the GPGIs
 over the average tax revenue collected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
'probability of reaching some Nash equilibrium with full participation':
 For each run of the algorithm, we record whether a Nash equilibrium is
 reached and if so, whether all players participate at this Nash equilibrium.
 Then we compute the proportion of runs for which a Nash equilibrium with
 full participation is reached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename c75with9participants/CORSIAPlus.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename c75with9participants/Simple MGF.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename c75with9participants/MGF with AEPMFs.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

