\begin_layout Section
Legitimacy and the risk of the mechanisms triggering trade wars
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout the analysis we have assumed away the possibility that countries
 that do not participate in the mechanisms might oppose it and retaliate
 against the participating countries.
 The EU's experience from 2012 that we outline in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-EU's-unilateral"

\end_inset

 shows that this danger needs to be taken very seriously.
 At the time many observers were concerned that the policy might trigger
 a 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "trade war"
target "https://www.dw.com/en/eu-emissions-policy-threatens-to-trigger-trade-war/a-16048424"

\end_inset

.
 For evaluating which mechanism should best be initiated, we need to take
 into account how each possible mechanism will affect the probability of
 a trade war.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It seems plausible that the more a mechanism contributes to the welfare
 of non-participants, the less likely it is that they will oppose it.
 Firstly, this is because they have less material incentive to try to cause
 the mechanism to disappear.
 Secondly, the mechanism will presumably be more legitimate if the participating
 countries allocate most of the money to GPGIs rather than keeping it for
 themselves (as the EU did in 2012).
 The results from section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Proportion-of-money"

\end_inset

 suggest that the MGF mechanisms raise for GPGIs a greater proportion of
 the the tax revenue collected than CORSIA+ does.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another reason why the MGF mechanisms could have more legitimacy
 than CORSIA+: Allowing participating countries to decide how to allocate
 to GPGIs the money that they collect as taxes would accomodate the demands
 of several countries including Brasil and China, who 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "reportedly"
target "http://www.raes-montreal.org/html/en/body/events/lectures/2018/RAeSMB%20(2018.06.04)%20BeyondCORSIA.Lyle.pdf"

\end_inset

 in the context of the CORSIA negotiations reject the idea that the list
 of eligible offset standards should be determined by the ICAO Council and
 prefer that States be allowed to apply their own offset standards.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Andrew Murphy"
target "https://www.carbonbrief.org/corsia-un-plan-to-offset-growth-in-aviation-emissions-after-2020"

\end_inset

from the NGO Transport and Environment, who is an observer in the CORSIA
 negotiations: “The reason for China’s scepticism is that, as a point of
 principal, they don’t want to be told by a UN agency which offsets they
 have to use for their airlines.” 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These considerations thus all point in the direction of the MGF mechanisms
 having more legitimacy and incurring a lower probability of triggering
 a trade war.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\emph on
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "8 sec:Conclusion"

\end_inset

Conclusion and discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have found in the numerical simulations that the MGF with AEPMFs can
 achieve 29% more welfare than CORSIA+.
 Moreover, the outperformance of the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs over CORSIA+
 and the Simple MGF mechanism appears to be robust to relaxing the assumption
 that the retention rate parameter is chosen optimally for each mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One questionable assumption is that in the context of the mechanisms, the
 countries within each of the 12 regional blocks overcome their colletive
 action problems.
 This seems at first glance very implausible.
 However, in the context of the MGF mechanism with AEPMFs the gains from
 cooperation within each block might be particularly large, which presumably
 would make cooperation within each block more likely.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see this, consider for example the gains from cooperation for African
 countries that arise endogenously at the Nash equilibria described in section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Results-for-the"

\end_inset

: All African countries most benefit from money going to the Global Fund
 Against AIDS, TB and Malaria.
 By participating and giving money to this GPGI, African countries can cause
 not just the tax money that they collect to go to this GPGI but also additional
 money that comes from the AEPMF with Global Fund Against AIDS, TB and Malaria,
 CEPI and Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund, to which the Middle East
 allocates all its tax revenue.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another questionable assumption is the absence of any foresight that has
 been implicit in the iterated best response algorithm that we have used.
 In all of the mechanisms that we have studied here the following holds:
 by participating, one decreases the incremental cost for the others to
 join.
 Thus foresight would weigh in favor of joining, since by doing so one can
 cause joining to be more attractive (and thus more likely) for others.
 Taking into account this effect would presumably improve the performance
 of all the three mechanisms to a similar extent.
 However, there is a further effect specific to the MGF with AEPMFs: By
 giving to an AEPMF for a set 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 of GPGIs, one can increase the incentives to join for others who strongly
 prefer some GPGI from 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 over the other GPGIs in 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

.
 This suggests that if one were to assume that players reason with foresight,
 then the performance of the MFG mechanism with AEPMFs would be improved
 by more than that of the other mechanisms.
 Future modelling work could investigate whether the conclusions of this
 line of informal reasoning do in fact hold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another important further research question is how the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of eligible GPGIs will affect the performance of the MGF mechanisms.
 It is plausible that by adding further GPGIs which benefit different players,
 the performance of the MGF mechanisms will typically be improved.
 This would suggest that it might be good to add a global fund that would
 buy up fossil fuel deposits that are marginally profitable, as suggested
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Harstad (2012)"
target "https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/10.1086/665405"

\end_inset

.
 This will benefit the countries possessing such deposits, as they will
 earn rents from the sale of the deposits.
 Another institution to add to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 could be a fund that would reward countries for funding research on clean
 energy.
 Such a fund could build on the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Mission Innovation Initiative"
target "http://mission-innovation.net/"

\end_inset

 that was established in 2015.
 A better understanding of the effect of the set S on the performance of
 the mechanisms could be useful for informing the initial choice for the
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 when the mechanism is started.
 Moreover, it could also help in the design of mechanisms for updating the
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 over time.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\start_of_appendix

\series bold
\size larger
Appendix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Matlab programs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Matlab code with which all the simulations were computed is available
 here: https://github.com/gpgi-financing/mgf-mechanisms.
 Running the script 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

main.m
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will redo all the simulations and also produce all the graphs displayed
 in this paper, with a run time of 8 hours.
 In section 1.1 of the script all the parameters are listed for which I guessed
 the values.
 The reader is encouraged to modify these parameters and rerun the simulations.
 The reader can also send me the profiles of these parameter values that
 he finds most plausible.
 I will run the simulations for these parameter values and report in https://git
hub.com/gpgi-financing/mgf-mechanisms/tree/master/figures the results, as
 well as any explanations for the guess of parameter values that the correspondi
ng reader wants to provide.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\emph on
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Explanation"

\end_inset

 Estimation of the payoffs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will compute values for the various parameters, using econometric
 estimates and data when possible, whilst resorting to ad hoc numerical
 assumptions for several of the parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=$
\end_inset

{Africa, China, EU, Eurasia, India, Japan, Latin America, Middle East, Other
 high income countries, Russia, other Asia} denote the set of players.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in K$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{k}$
\end_inset

 denote player 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

's payoff.
 Since we are assuming that each player's payoff is the sum of the payoffs
 of the countries that it comprises, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{k}=\sum_{i\in k}u_{i}=\sum_{i\in k}t_{i}-c_{i}xF_{i}+Y_{i}+b_{i}xG+\sum_{s\in S}\theta_{i}^{s}Z_{s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout we will assume that whilst in the games induced by the mechanisms
 countries coalesce into the 12 blocks given by the set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, they act individually otherwise.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These assumptions might appear inconsistent.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "8 sec:Conclusion"

\end_inset

 we provide reasons for why it is not implausible that for each of the players
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 the countries that constitute it overcome their collective action problems
 in the context of the MGF mechanisms.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-tax-burden"

\end_inset

The tax burden coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the redistributive effects 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity we shall assume throughout that the tax on the carbon emissions
 is equivalent to an ad valorem tax and that there are only scale effects.
 In other words, we neglect the fact that airlines will reduce emissions
 not just by decreasing the number of flights but also through other ways
 such as by increasing load factors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will assume that the tax rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is fixed and small.
 Let us consider 
\begin_inset Formula $-c_{i}xF_{i}+Y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in our linear separability assumptions, i.e.
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=\sigma_{i}+\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}=\sum_{j\neq i,k\neq i:j\,or\,k\,participate}\gamma_{ijk}xf_{jk}$
\end_inset

 we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\sum_{i\in k}c_{i}xF_{i}+Y_{i}=-\sum_{i\in k}(\sigma_{i}+\eta_{i})xF_{i}+\sum_{j\neq i,l\neq i:j\,or\,l\,participate}\gamma_{ijl}xf_{jl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall from section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:A-model-1"

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to redistributive effects such as the shifting of rents from
 tourism across countries and terms of trade effects.
 We shall assume that these effects are zero-sum for the world as a whole.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}(-\sum_{i\in k}\eta_{i}\text{+\sum_{j≠i,l≠i:j\,or\,l\,participate}\gamma_{ijl}xf_{jl}})=0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, to compute aggregate welfare we can simply ignore the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{ijk}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall assume throughout that each country internalises only the welfare
 of its own citizens.
 Thus when we sum the welfare effects 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}\sigma_{i}xF_{i}$
\end_inset

 over the set of all countries, each consumer is counted exactly once.
 We shall assume that for global welfare excluding climate change externalities,
 the marginal tax burden from international aviation is equal to that of
 other taxes
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Atkinson Stiglitz"
target "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/0047272776900414"

\end_inset

theorem (1976) would predict that the marginal tax burden (excluding externaliti
es) from taxes on international aviation is less than that of other taxes,
 since international aviation is currently taxed much less than other commoditie
s.
 However, we assume equality for simplicity and transparency.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 More precisely, we shall assume that this marginal tax burden from internationa
l aviation (excluding externalities) is 1 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
see 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Jacobs (2018)"
target "https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10797-017-9481-0"

\end_inset

 for a justification
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}\sigma_{i}xF_{i}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i\in I}xF_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 For simplicity and transparency we shall assume that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 are all equal, which implies that they are all equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us assume that at the status quo each country has optimally (from its
 own perspective) chosen its level of taxation on international aviation,
 assuming that it can retain the tax revenue raised from it
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The current profile of ticket taxes could indeed be interpreted as a Nash
 equilibrium in a game where each country acts individually.
 Countries do not coordinate on ticket taxes.
 Moreover,by now it appears to be accepted that it is legal for each country
 to set ticket taxes (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Faber and Huigen 2018"
target "https://www.transportenvironment.org/sites/te/files/publications/2018_12_CE_Delft_7L14_A_study_on_aviation_ticket_taxes_DEF.pdf"

\end_inset

).
 Hence each individual countries choice of ticket tax can be ssen as a best
 response.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
However, taxes on emissions are likely to have a lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 (see Stern (forthcoming) for a theoretical analysis suggesting that switching
 from ticket taxes to emissions taxes will increase welfare by increasing
 load factors).
 The current absence of emissions taxes is the result of legal obstacles
 mentioned in (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Larrson et al 2018"
target "https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/14693062.2018.1562871"

\end_inset

).
 We leave it for future work to refine the model by taking these effects
 into account.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}+\eta_{i}=1\forall i$
\end_inset

.
 Given that
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}=0.5\forall i,$
\end_inset

 we thus obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}=0.5\forall i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us rearrange
\begin_inset Formula $-\sum_{i\in k}(\sigma_{i}+\eta_{i})xF_{i}+\sum_{j\neq i,l\neq i:j\,or\,l\,participate}\gamma_{ijl}xf_{jl}$
\end_inset

 to separate out the part that is affected by whether or not player 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 participates:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(-\sum_{i\in k}(\sigma_{i}+\eta_{i})xF_{i}+\sum_{j\neq i,l\neq i:j\,or\,l\,participate\,and\,j\in k\,or\,l\in k}\gamma_{ijl}xf_{jl})+\sum_{j\neq i,l\neq i:j\,or\,l\,participate,\,j\notin k,l\notin k}\gamma_{ijl}xf_{jl}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j\neq i,l\neq i:j\,or\,l\,participate\,and\,j\in k\,or\,l\in k}\gamma_{ijl}xf_{jl}$
\end_inset

 is the redistributive effect that the countries making up player 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 will internalise thanks to the fact that they have coalesced into a single
 player in the context of the mechanisms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall make the ad hoc assumption that each of the players that consist
 of several countries internalises half of the redistributive effects.
 As a result, we can now write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $-\sum_{i\in k}c_{i}xF_{i}+Y_{i}=-\tilde{c_{k}}x\sum_{i\in k}F_{i}+\sum_{j\neq i,l\neq i:j\,or\,l\,participate,\,j\notin k,l\notin k}\gamma_{ijl}xf_{jl}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{c_{k}}=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 consist of a single country (which is the case for k=China, India, Japan,
 Russia, US) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{c_{k}}=0.75$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 consists of several countries (which is the case for k=Africa, EU, Eurasia,
 Latin America, Middle East, Other high income countries, other Asia).
 Moreover, only 
\begin_inset Formula $-\tilde{c_{k}}x\sum_{i\in k}F_{i}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j\neq i,l\neq i:j\,or\,l\,participate,\,j\notin k,l\notin k}\gamma_{ijl}xf_{jl}$
\end_inset

 is affected by the choice of player 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The flight matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate the network of emissions from international flights we use WorldPop'
s open source 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "global flight data"
target "https://www.worldpop.org/project/categories?id=13"

\end_inset

.
 From this data we computed for each pair of airports A and B the available
 seat kilometers by multiplying the estimated number of seats flying directly
 from A to B by the spherical distance computed from the longitudes and
 latitudes.
 These numbers were taken for the simulations as an estimate for the associated
 greenhouse gas emissions.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In december 2019 all participants to CORSIA will report 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emissions data"
target "http://www.universalweather.com/aviation-emissions/corsia/"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-global-effects"

\end_inset

The global effects 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b_{i}(x)}$
\end_inset

 from the emissions taxes on flights 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As stated in the previous section, we assume that the taxes on the aviation
 emissions are equivalent to an ad valorem tax and that there are only scale
 effects.
 In other words, we neglect the fact that airlines will reduce emissions
 not just by decreasing the number of flights but also through other ways
 such as by increasing load factors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned before, we take into account two global effects that are caused
 by the reduction in oil consumption induced by a tax on aviation emissions:
 a reduction in climate change damages and a reduction in the oil price.
 We shall assume that the supply of flights is infinitely price elastic.
 The elasticity of aviation demand is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{D}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First let us compute the reduction in climate change damages.
 For this, consider a carbon tax equal to 1% of ticket prices.
 Such a tax will reduce aviation emissions by 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{D}$
\end_inset

 percent.
 The total annual of emissions 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emissions"
target "https://www.atag.org/facts-figures.html"

\end_inset

 from aviation are 859 million tonnes of CO2.
 In line with 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Nordhaus (2017)"
target "https://www.pnas.org/content/pnas/114/7/1518.full.pdf"

\end_inset

 we assume a social cost of carbon of 
\begin_inset Formula $\$36$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The relevant concept of social cost of carbon for our purposes is descriptive:
 For predicting the evolution of the game, as we will try to to in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Numerical-simulations"

\end_inset

, we need to estimate how governments will in fact evaluate the benefits
 of climate change mitigation.
 Whilst the normative arguments against pure time discounting are compelling,
 it seems more plausible to model countries as agents that use pure time
 discounting, as done in the RICE model, on which the $36 SCC estimate is
 based.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "IPCC estimates"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environmental_impact_of_aviation#Total_climate_effects"

\end_inset

that the climate forcing effect of aviation emissions is 3 times that of
 its carbon content, due to the high altitudes at which they take place.
 Based on this, we assume that the social cost of aviation is 3 times that
 of its CO2 content contribution.
 Thus the total social cost of carbon from aviation is 
\begin_inset Formula $3\cdot\$36\cdot859\cdot10^{6}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The carbon tax of 1% of ticket prices thus averts 
\begin_inset Formula $3\cdot\$36\cdot859\cdot10^{6}\cdot1\%\cdot\epsilon_{D}$
\end_inset

 of net climate damages.
 Since the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "annual revenue"
target "https://www.statista.com/statistics/278372/revenue-of-commercial-airlines-worldwide/"

\end_inset

 of the aviation industry is 
\begin_inset Formula $\$855\cdot10^{9}$
\end_inset

, the revenue generated by the carbon tax of 1% of ticket prices is approximatel
y 
\begin_inset Formula $\$855\cdot10^{9}\cdot1\%$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we obtain that per dollar of carbon tax collected the averted climate
 change damages are equal to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $aggregate\,averted\,climate\,change\,damage=\frac{3\cdot\$36\cdot859\cdot10^{6}\cdot\epsilon_{D}}{\$855\cdot10^{9}}=0.108\cdot\epsilon_{D}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "IATA"
target "https://www.iata.org/whatwedo/documents/economics/air_travel_demand.pdf"

\end_inset

 an estimate of the average price elasticity of demand is available, which
 is 0.6.
 This estimate is an average of elasticities for price changes within and
 between regions closely corresponding to the regional blocks that are the
 players in our model.
 Thus these estimates do not take into account substitution to flights to
 other regions.
 We shall assume that 50% of the reduction in demand caused by an increase
 in the tax on aviation emissions within a region or between two regions
 leads to substitution to flights to other regions.
 Thus we need to multiply our estimate by 0.5, giving us 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{D}=0.5\cdot0.6=0.3$
\end_inset

.
 With this we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $aggregate\,averted\,climate\,change\,damage=0.0326$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us compute the redistributive effect that happens due to the change
 in oil prices on the world market.
 Our assumption of an infinitely elastic supply of aviation imples that
 per dollar of tax revenue raised from the taxes on the emissions, the reduction
 in revenue of the aviation industry is 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{D}$
\end_inset

 dollars 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We neglect here the possibility that the tax on emissions will lead airlines
 to reduce emission in other ways than reducing the number of flights, e.g.
 by increasing load factors.
 Taking into account these effects would lead to larger estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{D}$
\end_inset

 is the demand elasticity.
 In order to obtain the reduction in the expenditure on oil for aviation
 fuel, we need to multiply by the proportion of aviation costs due to fuel,
 which gives us:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $proportion\,of\,cost\,due\,to\,fuel\cdot\epsilon_{D}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By multiplying by the oil change ratio, we obtain the savings for oil consumers
 that this causes through the reduction in the price of oil.
 To obtain the losses for crude oil producers, we have to multiply by the
 ratio of aggregate net oil imports over aggregate oil consumption, giving
 us:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $losses\,for\,crude\,oil\,producers$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $=\frac{aggregate\,net\,oil\,imports}{aggregate\,oil\,consumption}\cdot oil\,change\,ratio\cdot proportion\,of\,cost\,due\,to\,fuel\cdot\epsilon_{D}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Enerdata"
target "https://yearbook.enerdata.net/crude-oil/crude-oil-balance-trade-data.html"

\end_inset

 we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{aggregate\,net\,oil\,imports}{aggregate\,oil\,consumption}=0.479$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "IATA (2018)"
target "https://www.iata.org/pressroom/facts_figures/fact_sheets/documents/fact-sheet-fuel.pdf"

\end_inset

 we take the estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $proportion\,of\,cost\,due\,to\,fuel=0.235$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Stoft (2008)"
target "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1300126"

\end_inset

 we take the estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $oil\,change\,ratio=1.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging in these numbers give that per dollar raised via aviation emissions
 taxes we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $losses\,for\,crude\,oil\,producers=0.0506$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These marginal losses for crude oil producers are of course equal to the
 marginal gains for gains for oil consumers.
 To compute the aggregate redistributive effect for each of the 12 players,
 we use data for crude oil production and oil consumption from 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Enerdata"
target "https://yearbook.enerdata.net/crude-oil/crude-oil-balance-trade-data"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summing the climate change damage reduction effect and effect via the changes
 in world oil prices gives us the following estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b_{k}}:=\sum_{i\in k}b_{i}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 ranges over the 12 players:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MGF/AEPMF/aepmf/aepmf2/bEstimates.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Effects-of-the"

\end_inset

Effects of the money raised for the GPGIs: 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{s}^{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

payoff estimates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that we now compute will be based on two types of parameters which we will
 not determine based on data but instead guess: Firstly, ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since one of the question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effects per dollar given to the Fund buying up CDM certificates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the marginal abatement cost curve for registered CDM projects (from
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Shishlov (2014)"
target "https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Marginal-abatement-cost-curve-in-2013-2020-for-registered-CDM-projects-2_fig1_281792968"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MGF/seminar presentation/Marginal-abatement-cost-curve-in-2013-2020-for-registered-CDM-projects-2.png
	scale 55

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can think of the Clean Development Mechanism as a if it was a principal
 contracting with project owners who are the agents in the mechanism.
 The specific mechanism implemented by the CDM is to pay project owners
 an amount proportional to the abated emissions.
 In practice the payment per abated emissions is of course the market price
 of carbon offsets, which fluctuates over time.
 However, we shall abstract away from this feature and pretend that everything
 is static.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The abatement costs of any individual project is private information to
 the project owner who will earn informational rents.
 If the principal had perfect information, he could cause the same projects
 to happen as he does under the actual mechanism, whilst not leaving any
 rents to the agents.
 This he could hypothetically do by making each agent a take-it-or-leave-it
 offer for doing the project, offering the project owner just enough money
 to make him indifferent between accepting the offer or not.
 The actual mechanism can now be viewed as a combination of this hypothetical
 contracting under perfect information and paying out gifts equal to the
 informational rents in the actual mechanism.
 We can view the first part in this combination as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

purchasing the global public good of reducing emissions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the second part as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

giving out informational rents
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CDM has been criticised for having large rents (ref).
 However, increasingly, low cost abatement categories are covered under
 other mechanisms and are thus no longer eligible for new CDM projects.
 For example, HFCs are covered under the 2016 Kigali amendment to the Montreal
 protocol.
 Hence informational rents are getting smaller.
 This motivatess the following (admittedly ad hoc) assumption: We assume
 that in the actual CDM 50% of the money ends up being used for the purchasing
 the global public good of reducing emissions.
 This is illustrated in the following diagram:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MGF/seminar presentation/Fund for CDM payoffs final diagram.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 34

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that the players (i.e.
 Africa, China, EU, Eurasia, India, Japan, Latin America, Middle East, Other
 high income countries, Russia, other Asia) internalise the rents accruing
 to the owners of projects on their territory.
 Moreover, we assume that the distribution of rents is proportional to the
 amount of CERs (certified emissions reductions) for CDM projects on the
 players' territories.
 We take the latest 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "data"
target "[http://www.cdmpipeline.org/cdm-projects-region.htm]"

\end_inset

 found for this (counting all CERs until 2018) .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us turn to the effects of the actual emissions reductions.
 The players' payoffs are assumed to be affected in two ways.
 Firstly, the emissions reductions avert some climate change.
 We shall now make the ad hoc assumption that per dollar used to purchase
 emissions reductions 2.5 dollars of net global benefits arise
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This number is broadly consistent with our assumption that the social cost
 of carbon is $36 per ton of CO2.
 To see this, suppose that the marginal abatement cost of the projects funded
 via the CDM will be $10, in line with the marginal abatement cost curve
 shown above.
 This would imply that the benefit cost ratio would be 3.6.
 However, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Cames et al (2016)"
target "https://ec.europa.eu/clima/sites/clima/files/ets/docs/clean_dev_mechanism_en.pdf"

\end_inset

 find that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

73% of the potential 2013-2020 Certified Emissions Reduction (CER) supply
 have a low likelihood that emission reductions are additional and are not
 over-estimated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, so so we should substantially revise our number downwards from 3.6.
 This makes 2 seem reasonable.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We assume that the distribution of these effects is proportional to the
 estimates from the RICE model (from Nordhaus 2010, also listed on page
 14 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Nordhaus (2015)"
target "https://economics.stanford.edu/sites/g/files/sbiybj9386/f/climateclub_022715-appendix.pdf"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Actually, to compute the overall payoffs, we make a slight adjustment because
 of the functioning of the clean development mechanism.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "the CDM guidelines "
target "https://cdm.unfccc.int/methodologies/PAmethodologies/tools/am-tool-02-v7.0.pdf"

\end_inset

 projects are only eligible for receiving emissions reductions certificates
 if they can prove that they would not be profitable without the money from
 the sale of these certificates.
 One can show that if the marginal abatement cost curve is linear then the
 CDM does not change the incentives for the national government setting
 its subsidy for renewables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The marginal abatement cost curve reported above already takes into account
 any national subsidies.
 The effective subsidy that project owners face is the sum of the national
 subsidy and the market price of the certificates for certified emissions
 reductions.
 We assume that the national subsidies are set individually optimally by
 each government.
 Therefore it is equal to the local externalities plus the global effects
 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-global-effects"

\end_inset

) that the country internalises.
 From this it follows that an additional project that happens due to the
 CDM causes not only the global benefits but also causes costs equal to
 the subsidy in place in the country where the project takes place.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In other words, since we assume that countries already set their national
 subsidies optimally from their perspectives, the global net benefit that
 an additional projects causes is computed by summing the benefits accruing
 to all the other countries but not to the country where the project takes
 place.
 Otherwise we would be double-counting.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second effect arising from emissions reductions is a redistribution
 from net oil exporters to net oil importers.
 From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-global-effects"

\end_inset

 we know what this effect would be if all the emissions reductions were
 realised through reductions in oil consumption.
 Based on the data provided in http://www.cdmpipeline.org/cdm-projects-type.htm,
 I make the preliminary guess that the proportion of the CDM's emissions
 reductions that are through reduced oil demand is 0.2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effects per dollar given to ITER (The International Thermonuclear Reactor)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ITER has so far been financed through voluntary contributions by European
 Union, India, Japan, China, Russia, South Korea, and the United States.
 These countries will own the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "intellectual property"
target "https://www.iter.org/intellectualproperty"

\end_inset

 that is generated, thus conferring rents to them.
 Whenever additional money is added to ITER (and assuming that the rules
 for access to the technology are not changed), the expected value of these
 rents is increased.
 Specifically, we will assume that the expected value of rents is increased
 by $0.5 for every $1 added to ITER.
 Analogously to our analysis of the CDM, we can think of a dollar reaching
 ITER to be split: $0.5 are given out as rents and the remaining $0.5 are
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

used to purchase the global public good of reducing emissions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 We assume that the rents accruing to the participating countries are proportion
al to the amounts of 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "net cash contributions"
target "https://blogs-images.forbes.com/niallmccarthy/files/2014/10/20141020_ITER _Fo _Final.jpg"

\end_inset

 that they make.
 As far as the effects of the expected emssions reductions are concerned,
 the situation is assumed to be identical to the CDM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MGF/seminar presentation/ITER payoffs final diagram.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 34

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effects per dollar given to the Carbon Pricing Reward Fund
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast to the other 5 GPGIs that we consider, the Carbon Pricing Reward
 Fund does not yet exist.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Cramton Stoft (2011)"
target "https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/6362845.pdf"

\end_inset

 propose to create a global fund that would reward countries based both
 on how much they emit and how much net carbon tax revenue (i.e.
 carbon tax revenue minus fossil fuel subsidies) they collect (all sectors
 of the economy included).
 We shall consider the following version of this kind of proposal
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cramton and Stoft's proposal is to use an additive reward payment function,
 instead of the multiplicative that we consider here.
 The reasons why we consider the multiplicative function here are that it
 leads to more of the informational rents accruing to low income countries
 and stronger incentives for them to reduce fossil fuel subsidies and to
 tax carbon.
 Assuming higher marginal utility of money in these countries, shifting
 informational rents to them is beneficial.
 Moreover, in these countries the removal of fossil fuel subsidies and the
 introduction of carbon taxes are very progressive in their distributional
 effects (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Sterner et al 2012"
target "https://books.google.de/books?hl=de&lr=&id=iurFBQAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PT10&dq=sterner+incidence+of+carbon+taxes+in+developing+countries&ots=FFXC41VXMh&sig=m1JUdRkFhhVYDWU9XQxrvozTedM#v=onepage&q=sterner%20incidence%20of%20carbon%20taxes%20in%20developing%20countries&f=false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Definition: 
\series bold
The multiplicative mechanism
\series default
 makes reward payments to countries based on their per capita consumption
 based emissions 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, their net per capita carbon tax revenue 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and their population 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 according to the formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f*max(0,\hat{Q}-Q)*max(0,R-\hat{R})P$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 are fixed constants and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is endogenously adjusted so that the fund exactly uses up its budget.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will assume that the Carbon Pricing Reward Fund uses the multiplicative
 mechansim.
 Given that the policies that the Carbon Pricing Reward would incentivise
 are very cost-effective, the question arises as to why such a mechanism
 does not already exist.
 One explanation could be that a large proportion of the money would end
 up accruing as informational rents.
 Based on this, we make the ad hoc assumption that per dollar given to the
 Carbon Pricing Reward Fund 0.8 dollar end up accruing as informational rents,
 as illustrated in the diagram:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MGF/seminar presentation/Multiplicative mechanism   final.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 34

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As long as the budget of the Carbon Pricing Reward Fund is small, the informatio
nal rents accruing to countries are proportional to the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f*max(0,\hat{Q}-Q)*max(0,R-\hat{R})P$
\end_inset

 that we obtain by substituting in the status quo values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 This is a consequence of the envelope theorem.
 To compute the status quo consumption based emissions we use 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "the available estimates"
target "https://www.pnas.org/content/108/21/8903 "

\end_inset

 and for the countries for which such estimates were not available, we use
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "the production based figures"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_carbon_dioxide_emissions_per_capita"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The threshold values were taken to be:
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}=1$
\end_inset

 metric tons of CO2 emissions per person per year, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}=-\$10$
\end_inset

0 per person per year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concerning the 0.2 dollars that do not accrue as informational rents, we
 make the ad hoc assumption that the multiplicative mechanism is 1.5 times
 as efficient at reducing emissions as the CDM.
 To compute the amount of oil rent redistribution, we proceed as follows:
 First we compute what this effect would be if all the emissions reductions
 achieved were through decreased oil consumption, using that in this case
 the ratio of the oil rent redistribution to the climate benefit would have
 to be the same as we obtained in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-global-effects"

\end_inset

.
 However, we need to adjust this estimate, since part of the emissions reduction
s that the Carbon Pricing Reward Fund would induce could be in the form
 of reductions in coal and gas consumption.
 We make the ad hoc assumption that we have to multiply our estimate by
 0.75 in order to get the true value of the oil rent redistribution effect.
  Unfortnuately, the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "data"
target "https://www.imf.org/external/error.htm?URL=http://www.imf.org/external/np/fad/subsidies/data/wpdata.xlsx"

\end_inset

 used only had the aggregate fossil fuel subsidies and not the subsidies
 for coal, oil and gas separately, so that so far we have not been able
 to compute a proper estimate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effects per dollar given to the Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Forest Carbon Partnership rewards countries with tropical forests for
 conserving them.
 An elaborate methodology has been developed through which reference levels
 of deforestation are determined.
 Reward payments are made for reductions in deforestation below the reference
 levels.
 This is in contrast to the Carbon Pricing Reward Fund proposals, where
 reference levels are not differentiated across countries.
 This suggests that we should assume that the Forest Carbon Partnership's
 Carbon Fund will generate less informational rents than the Carbon Pricing
 Reward Fund and motivates our ad hoc assumption that per dollar given to
 this GPGI 0.5 dollar accrue as informational rents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we can think of an additional dollar as doing a combination two things:
 Firstly, paying out informational rents and secondly, purchasing the global
 public good (in this case reducing emission due to tropical deforestation)
 by compensating the agents in the mechanism (in this case national and
 local governments) for the costs incurred to increase the provision of
 the global public good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename MGF/seminar presentation/FCP carbon fund final.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 34

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We make the ad hoc assumption that per dollar used to purchase the global
 public good of reducing emissions, 2.1 dollars of aggregate benefits are
 generated globally via averted climate change.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Analogously to the case of the CDM, we assume that the status quo each country
 chooses its level of forest conservation selfishly optimal, taking into
 account that it internalises a part of the global effects of climate change
 mitigation.
 Thus the net global benefits of an emissions reduction taking place in
 a given country is equal to the sum of the global effects accruing to all
 the other countries.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number 2.1 is chosen so as to ensure that the assumptions are favorable
 to the CORSIA+ mechanism, relative to which we will evaluate the newly
 proposed MGF mechanisms (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Effects-per-dollar"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is also a potentially important redistributive general equilibrium
 effect that we need to take into account: Some of the forest conservation
 measures that will be taken in response to the incentive payments provided
 by the Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund will entail reducing the
 production of commodities such as palm oil, pulp, paper, timber and soy
 beans that are produced by the countries with tropical forests.
 As a result, the world market price of these commodities increases, which
 benefits the sellers of these commodities.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Harstad and Mideksa (2017)"
target "https://academic.oup.com/restud/article-abstract/84/4/1708/3069929"

\end_inset

 point to a countervailing effect that also needs to be taken into account:
 Higher prices for the commodities driving deforestation makes illeal logging
 more profitable, thereby making enforcement of conservation more costly.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The flip side of this is of course that the buyers of these commodities
 loose out.
 We make the ad hoc assumption that per dollar used to purchase emissions
 reductions, 0.5 dollars of benefits accrue to the sellers.
 We assume that consumption of these commodities is proportional to GDP
 and that the production is proportional to the tropical forest cover.
 We leave it for future work to generate proper estimates using data on
 all the commodities that drive deforestation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effects per dollar given to CEPI (the Coalition For Epidemic Preparedness
 Innovation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CEPI has so far mostly been focussing on advancing vaccines against known
 threats.
 Recently, it has started to also fund new platform technologies with the
 potential to accelerate the development and manufacture of vaccines against
 previously unknown pathogens.
 Particularly this latter category brings benefits for all countries, since
 future novel pathogens might cause global pandemics.
 Based on this, we make the assumption that the benefits of money going
 to CEPI accrue to all countries in proportion to their GDP.
 Moreover, we make the ad hoc assumption that per dollar eaching CEPI 1.5
 dollars of global benefits are created.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effects per dollar given to the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, TB and Malaria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Global Fund gives grants for programs agains AIDS, TB and Malaria.
 Allocations are calculated using a formula based on a country's disease
 burden and economic capacity.
 Of the total amount allocated to each country, at least 15 percent are
 made available as matching offers to encourage countries to make additional
 investments in their response to the three diseases.
 To access the incentive portion of their allocation, countries will need
 to commit to additional co-financing investments over and above previous
 levels of spending.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some countries 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "do not take up"
target "http://www.aidspan.org/fr/node/4766"

\end_inset

 these 1:1 matching offers, thereby reaviling that they value a dollar earmarked
 for these health programs strictly less than a dollar with no strings attached.
 If there were no cross-country externalities, then we would have to conclude
 the aggregate global benefit
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
By 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

global benefit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 we of cause always mean the aggregate payoffs, summed over all countries.
 This revealed preference notion of benefits is the relevant concept when
 it comes to studying the incentives countries have to participate in the
 mechanissm.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of a dollar given to the Global Fund is less than 1.
 However, taking into account the cross-country externalities weighs in
 favor of assuming a larger benefit cost ratio.
 We make the ad hoc assumption that the actual benefit cost ratio for a
 dollar given to the Global Fund is 1.
 Moreover, we will assume that the benefits accrue to countries in proportion
 to the money that they received from the Global Fund during the period
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "2016-2019"
target "xhttps://www.theglobalfund.org/media/5649/core_overviewofallocations20172019_overview_en.pdf"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Effects-per-dollar"

\end_inset

Effects per dollar raised under CORSIA+
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we assume that the effect is the average between the effect of the
 Fund buying up CDM certificates and the Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon
 Fund.
 This is motivated by the observation that it is 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "likely"
target "https://carbonmarketwatch.org/publications/31111/"

\end_inset

 that under CORSIA both offsets for projects like in the CDM (e.g.
 renewable energy projects) and projects for reducing tropical deforestation
 will be accepted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Estimates-of-Payoffs"

\end_inset

Estimates of Payoffs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Effects of the money raised for the GPGIs: 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{s}^{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we report the payoffs that we obtain by using the assumptions detailed
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
