\begin_layout Standard
As explained before, we are assuming that the payoff per dollar raised for
 the climate change mitigation GPGI under CORSIA+ is the average of the
 payoff per dollar raised for the Fund buing up CDM certificates and the
 Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund.
 From the number for the aggregate payoffs we see that our assumptions are
 favorable to CORSIA+.
 Despite this, however, in the simulations reported in the next section
 the MGF mechanisms outperform CORSIA+.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Transposition of the MGF mechanisms to alternative tax bases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have focused so far on mechanisms based on the taxation of greenhouse
 gas emissions from international aviation.
 However, the mechanism can be transposed to other tax bases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Emissions from International Maritime Shipping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was long considered to be infeasible to design a mechanism for taxing
 maritime shipping that could be initiated by a subset of countries, given
 the ease with which ships can avoid fuel taxes by fueling in jurisdictions
 that do not participate, and given the host of international legal constraints
 that apply.
 However, thanks to a recent concerted effort of legal scholars and economists
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Heine et al (2017)"
target "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2512747"

\end_inset

) a proposal has been elaborated that navigates all these constraints and
 appears to be waterproof to evasion problems.
 The MGF mechanisms that we have proposed here can be combined with the
 taxation mechanism defined by by Heine et al.
 (2015).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
taxation obligation: tax the 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Luxury goods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taxes on luxury goods 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "have been discussed"
target "http://www.un.org/en/development/desa/policy/wess/wess_current/2012wess_overview_en.pdf"

\end_inset

 as a potential source for financing global public goods.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Ng (1987)"
target "http://www3.ntu.edu.sg/home/ykng/Ng1987%20diamond.pdf"

\end_inset

 shows that taxes on some luxury goods such a jewelry might be burden-free,
 since people buy them to signal via these goods' prices.
 Current tax rates on luxury goods appear to be a result of a coordination
 problem between countries: China lowered its taxes on luxury goods in 2016
 so as to reduce the profit margins for people who buy luxury goods abroad,
 evade customs in China and resell them there.
 These high profit margins for smugglers only exist because when buying
 goods abroad, people can get VAT refunds when they return to their home
 country.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All this suggests that through additional taxes on luxury goods money could
 be raised with a very low associated global tax burden.
 A design task is how to adapt the taxation obligation in the MGF mechanisms
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Definition-of-Proposal 1"

\end_inset

) to the case of luxury goods.
 One possibility could be as follows: Each participant would have to tax
 the sale of all luxury goods on their territory at a rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, each participant would have to tax all exports of luxury goods
 to non-participating countries at the rate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, he would have to tax all exports of intermediate goods used
 to produce luxury goods in non-participating countries (e.g.
 raw diamonds for jewelry production) at some rate 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, which could be calibrated so as to achieve that in non-participating countries
 similar overall taxes weigh on luxury goods.
 The allocation obligation could be kept identical to the one in the original
 MGF mechnanisms (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Definition-of-Proposal 1"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This proposal would violate the destination principle for indirect taxes
 and as such might be inconsistent with existing WTO agreements (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "chapter 7"
target "https://www.ifs.org.uk/uploads/mirrleesreview/design/ch7.pdf"

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Mirrlees et al. (2011)"
target "https://www.ifs.org.uk/uploads/mirrleesreview/design/ch7.pdf"

\end_inset

).
 However, if most of the tax revenu collected via the mechanism is raised
 for Global Public Good Institutions, it is plausible that the mechanism
 would have enough legitimacy so as to allow an exemption to the destination
 principle for it.
\end_layout

